type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Our <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-0044.xml"
addr="jms-0044"
title="Splitting the generic element of the generic cone">splitting of the generic element of the generic cone</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\Delta  I}\xrightarrow {{p}}{1_{{A}\downarrow {\mathcal {U}}}}]]></fr:tex> over the identity functor on reflection algebras <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-003E.xml"
addr="jms-003E"
title="A wild universal cone from a splitting of the generic element">yields a new (incoherent) cone</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\Delta  J}\xrightarrow {{q}}{1_{{A}\downarrow {\mathcal {U}}}}]]></fr:tex> whose generic element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{J}:J\multimap  J]]></fr:tex> may be identified with the identity homomorphism. It <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-003B.xml"
addr="jms-003B"
title="Wild initial objects from universal cones">follows</fr:link> that each  space of homomorphisms <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J\to  X]]></fr:tex> is contractible. Therefore, we define <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A_{\mathcal {U}}]]></fr:tex> to be the apex <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
